'''Alex Ferrari''' (born 1 July 1994) is an Italian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|defender]] for [[Serie A]] club [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]].

==Club career==
Ferrari was born in [[Modena]]. He played for lowly Modena Est, before joining [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]'s youth setup in 2002, aged eight,<ref>[http://www.zerocinquantuno.it/rubriche/largo-ai-giovani/8372-alex-ferrari-ho-piu-fiducia-in-me-stesso.html Alex Ferrari: "Ho più fiducia in me stesso" (Alex Ferrari: "I have more self confidence")]; Zero Cinquanto, 27 March 2013 (in Italian)  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517152207/http://www.zerocinquantuno.it/rubriche/largo-ai-giovani/8372-alex-ferrari-ho-piu-fiducia-in-me-stesso.html |date=17 May 2014 }}</ref> and was promoted to the Primavera squad in the mid–2011.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}

On 3 December 2013, Ferrari made his first-team debut, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 1–2 home loss against [[A.S. Siena|Siena]], for [[2013–14 Coppa Italia|the season]]'s [[Coppa Italia]].<ref>[http://www.ilrestodelcarlino.it/bologna/sport/calcio/2013/12/03/991677-bologna-siena-coppa-italia.shtml#1 Bologna fuori dalla Coppa Italia. Feddal fa felice il Siena al 122' (Bologna out of Coppa Italia. Feddal makes Siena happy in the 122nd minute)]; QN, 4 December 2013 (in Italian)</ref> On 14 January of the following year he was loaned to [[F.C. Crotone|Crotone]].<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/14-01-2014/bologna-ferrari-prestito-crotone-202067467917.shtml Bologna: Ferrari in prestito al Crotone (Bologna: Ferrari on loan to Crotone)]; [[La Gazzetta dello Sport]], 14 January 2014 (in Italian)</ref>

In January 2017 he signed a new 4½-year contract with Bologna.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/alex-ferrari-extends-contract/|title=Alex Ferrari extends contract|date=21 January 2017|access-date=25 January 2017|publisher=Bologna F.C. 1909}}</ref> He moved on loan to [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]] on 27 January 2017, lasting until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/ferrari-moves-to-hellas-verona-on-loan/|title=Ferrari moves to Hellas Verona on loan|publisher=Bologna F.C. 1909|accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref> On 12 July 2017, his loan at Verona was extended until June 2018, with an obligation to buy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/notizie/calciomercato-verona-ecco-ferrari-arriva-in-prestito-dal/18ova0ied8g5a1vw5ang3jfirz|title=CALCIOMERCATO VERONA, DOPPIO COLPO: TORNANO FERRARI E ZUCULINI|date=12 July 2017|access-date=6 September 2017|publisher=Goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/alex-ferrari-to-verona/|title=Alex Ferrari to Verona|date=12 July 2017|access-date=6 September 2017|publisher=Bologna F.C. 1909}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://hellasverona.it/2017/07/12/__1_2_3_4_5_6_7_8_9_10_11_12_13_14_15_16|title=Bentornati Alex Ferrari Franco Zuculini|trans-title=Welcome back Alex Ferrari, Franco Zuculini|date=12 July 2017|access-date=6 September 2017|publisher=Hellas Verona F.C.|language=Italian}}</ref>

On 13 June 2018, Ferrari signed to [[Serie A]] club [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], on loan until 30 June 2019 with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calcionews24.com/calciomercato-sampdoria-alex-ferrari-ufficiale-bologna/|title=Ferrari signed with  Sampdoria|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The deal was later turned permanent.<ref>[https://www.sampnews24.com/la-sampdoria-riparte-dai-suoi-punti-fissi-chi-rimane/ La Sampdoria riparte dai suoi punti fissi: chi rimane], sampnews24.com, 4 June 2019</ref>

==International career==
Ferrari made his debut with the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]] on 2 June 2016, in a friendly match against [[France national under-21 football team|France]].

In June 2017, he was included in the Italy under-21 squad for the [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] by manager [[Luigi Di Biagio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/103752/u21-italy-squad-euros-named|title=U21: Italy squad for Euros named|publisher=Football Italia|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> He made his only appearance of the tournament In Italy's second group match on 21 June, a 3–1 defeat to [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2017/matches/round=2000645/match=2021152/index.html |title=Czech Republic 3-1 Italy |publisher=UEFA.com |date=21 June 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2019 }}</ref> Italy were eliminated in the semi-finals following a 3–1 defeat to [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]] on 27 June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40425929#tab-2 |title=Spain U21 3-1 Italy U21 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 June 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2019 }}</ref>

